    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          The table below repeats the last three entries of  <xref
          ref="BasicIntegrationTable">Table</xref>. 
        </p>
        <table xml:id="InvereTrigIntegrationTable">
          <title>Inverse Trigonometric Substitution</title>
          <tabular halign="left">
            <row bottom="major" header="yes">
              <cell>Differentiation Rule</cell><cell><line>Integration Rule</line></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\sin(x))= \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sin(x)+c</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\tan(x))= \frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}=\inverse\tan(x)+c</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\sec(x))= \frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\int\frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sec(x)+c</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
        <p>
          You can memorize it if you like, but if you for get one of these
          formulas they are straightforward to derive.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the substitution <m>x=\sin(\theta)</m> to compute
