    <p>
      This is all well and good, but the forms <m>\sqrt{1-x^2}</m>,
      <m>\sqrt{1+x^2}</m>, and <m>\sqrt{x^2-1}</m> are all very
      specific. Can we use them for an integral like
      <m>
        \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{4+x^2}}\dx{x}
        </m>?
    </p>
    <p>
      Of course we can. We just need to rearrange it using Algebra.  Observe
      that if we had a <m>4</m> where the <m>1</m> is we'd be fine. We can't
      just change it. That would change the entire integral. But if we
      factor it out we get
      <men xml:id="TrigSubst1">
        \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{4+x^2}}\dx{x}=\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{4\left(1+\frac{x^2}{4}\right)}}\dx{x}=\frac12\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)^2}}\dx{x}
      </men>
    </p>
    <p>
      Of course, now we have another problem. We have
      <m>\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)^2</m> where we were happy to have
      <m>x^2</m> before. But since we were going to substitute <m>x</m> away
      anyhow we'll just substitute <m>\frac{x}{2}</m> away instead.
    </p>
    <p>
      Letting <m>\frac{x}{2}=\tan(\theta)</m>, we proceed as before.
    </p>

    <problem xml:id="TrigSubst2">
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Finish computing the integral in <xref ref="TrigSubst1">equation</xref>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{5-x^2}}\dx{x}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-9}}\dx{x}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-6x}}\dx{x}</m> 
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            This  appears to be a completely different integral but it really isn't. Complete the square on
            <m>x^2-6x</m> and then use your result in part (c).
          </p>
        </hint>
      </task>
    </problem>
    <p>
      It should be clear from <xref ref="TrigSubst2">Drill</xref> that as
      long as the expression inside the radical is a quadratic, we can
      manipulate it algebraically to produce something of the form
      <m>\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{x-b}{a}\right)^2}</m>,
      <m>\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{x-b}{a}\right)^2}</m>or <m>\sqrt{\left(\frac{x-b}{a}\right)^2-1}</m>.
      From there, we can use the appropriate trigonometric substitution.
    </p>

    <p>
      Earlier we computed terminal velocity when considering linear
      drag. Now we will compare this to terminal velocity when the drag is
      proportional to the square of the velocity. An example of this would
      be a ball of mass <m>M</m> falling in air. (We can include buoyancy
      again, but it is typically negligible so we will discount it). Again,
      to model this, let<m>y(t)</m> be distance the ball has fallen (so the
      positive <m>y</m> axis is pointing downward), with <m>y(0)=0</m>
      representing the initial position of the ball. In a similar analysis
      to before, we denote the acceleration due to gravity by <m>g</m>, so
      the weight of the ball is <m>Mg</m>. The drag, which we assume is now
      quadratic, is proportional to the square of the velocity, so we will
      denote this by <m>-Rv^2</m>, where <m>R</m> is a constant and
      <m>v=\dfdx{v}{t}</m> is the velocity. For simplicity, we will assume
      <m>v(0)=0</m>.
    </p>

    <exercise xml:id="FallingWithDrag">

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use Newton's Third Law of Motion:
            (<m>F</m>)<m>=</m>(<m>M</m>)ass<m>\cdot{}</m>(<m>A</m>)cceleration, to
            show that the velocity of the ball must satisfy the equations:
            <me>
              M\dfdx{v}{t}=Mg-Rv^2, \hskip5mm{}v(0)=0
              </me>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Show that the IVP above is equivalent to 
            <me>
              \frac{\dx{v}}{1-\frac{R}{Mg}v^2}=g\dx{t}, \hskip5mm v(0)=0
              </me>.
        </p></statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the substitution <m>\sqrt{\frac{R}{Mg}}v = \sin(\theta)</m> to
            show that
            <me>
              v=\sqrt{\frac{Mg}{R}}\left[\frac{1-e^{-2gt}}{1+e^{-2gt}}\right]
              </me>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\limit{t}{\infty}{v}</m>. Compare this terminal velocity
            with our previous results.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

    </exercise>

    <p>
      The trigonometric substitutions we've dealt with so far have  all
      involved square roots. What about this integral:
      <m>\int\frac{\dx{x}}{(1-x^2)^\frac32}</m>? Do you see that this is
      only slightly more complicated?
    </p>
    <p>
      If we make the substitution <m>x=\sin(\theta)</m>, then
      <m>\dx{x}=\cos(\theta)</m> as before so,
      <me>
        \int\frac{\dx{x}}{(1-x^2)^\frac32} =
        \int\frac{\cos(\theta)}{\left(\sqrt{1-\sin^2(\theta)}\right)^3}\dx{\theta}=\int\frac{\cos(\theta)}{\cos^3(\theta)}\dx{\theta}=\int\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}=\tan(\theta)+c
        </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Since <m>\sin(\theta)=\frac{x}{2}</m>, we get the triangle 
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>Image of the triangle</caption>
      <image source="TrigTri1.png" width="40%">
        <shortdescription>Image of the triangle with theta in standard position and legs x and square root of one - x squared.</shortdescription>
      </image> 
    </figure>
    <p>
      so
      <me>
        \int\frac{\dx{x}}{\left(x^2-1\right)^\frac32}=\tan(\theta)+c=\frac{x}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}+c
        </me>.
    </p>
    <problem>
      <p>
        Confirm that this is correct by differentiating:
        <m>\frac{x}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}+c</m>.
      </p>
    </problem>

    <p>
      Fortunately, we were still able to handle this, but what if we started
      with the integral:
      <m>\int\frac{x}{\left(x^2-1\right)^\frac32}\dx{x}{}</m>?
    </p>
    <p>
      The substitution <m>x=\sec(\theta)</m> leads to:
      <m>\int{\frac{\sec(\theta)}{\tan^2(\theta)}}\dx{\theta}</m>. 
      How do we handle that?
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title></title>
      <p>
        Confirm
        this yourself.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <p>
      We rewrite it as 
      <me>
        \int{\frac{\sec(\theta)}{\tan^2(\theta)}}\dx{\theta}=\int\frac{1/\cos(\theta)}{\sin^2(\theta)/\cos^2(\theta)}\dx{\theta}=\int\frac{\cos(\theta)}{\sin^2(\theta)}\dx{\theta}=\int\cot(\theta)\csc(\theta)\dx{\theta}=-\csc(\theta)+c
        </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      This example underscores the need to be able to compute a variety of
      integrals involving trigonometric functions. Again, it is a trial and
      error kind of thing, but there are some standard tricks to learn. It
      is probably best to learn these tricks by looking at some specific
      examples, but as you do, focus on the technique being used and how it
      can be used on similar integrals, not the specific example.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="OddSinPower">

      <p>
        <me>
          \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}
        </me>

        Since sine is raised to an odd power, it makes sense to <q>save one of
        the sines</q> and convert everything else to cosine, utilizing the
        Pythagorean identity <m>\sin^2(\theta)=1-\cos^2(\theta)</m>, and then
        apply a substitution as follows. First we <q>save a sine.</q>
        <me>
          \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta} =
          \int\sin(\theta)\sin^2(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}=\int(1-\cos^2(\theta))\cos^2(\theta)\sin(\theta)\dx{\theta}
          </me>.
          Next we let <m>z=\cos(\theta)</m>, so that
          <m>\dx{z}=-\sin(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>, which gives   
          <md>
            <mrow>\int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta} \amp=
            \int(1-z^2)z^2(-\dx{z})</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\int(z^4-z^2)\dx{z}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{z^5}{5}=\frac{z^3}{3}+c</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{\cos^5(\theta)}{5}=\frac{\cos^3(\theta)}{3}+c</mrow>
            </md>.
      </p>
    </example>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Had the cosine been raised to an odd power in <xref
          ref="OddSinPower">example</xref>, we could have <q>saved one
          of the cosines</q> instead.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\int\sin^2(\theta)\cos^3(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <example>
      <p>
        Notice that in <xref ref="OddSinPower">example</xref> there would
        have been nothing wrong with computing
        <m>\int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m> as  follows:
        <me>
          \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta} =
          \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos(\theta)\cos(\theta)\dx{\theta} =
          \int\sin^3(\theta)\sqrt{1-\sin^2(\theta)}\cos(\theta)\dx{\theta}
          </me>.  
          It's just that it is not immediately clear how to continue
          from here.  Most people will shy away from this because of the square
          root but in fact, this integral can be computed
          using techniques you already know.
      </p>
      <p>
        First, the elementary substitution <m>x=\sin(\theta)</m> will give: 
        <me>
          \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta} = \int
          x^3\sqrt{1-x^2}\dx{x}
          </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        You see why we wouldn't want to go this route, right? Recall that we
        introduced trigonometric substitutions precisely so we could handle
        integrals like this last one. It would seem to be counterproductive to
        take this path since we <em> started </em> with an integral involving
        trigonometric functions.
      </p>
      <p>
        While our goal is to be able to work out integrals by the simplest
        possible method, not the most difficult, it can instructive to see
        that a computation can be done in more than one manner so we will
        pursue this just a bit farther.
      </p>
    </example>
      <exercise>
        <introduction>
<p>
          Compute the integral <m>\int x^3\sqrt{1-x^2}\dx{x}</m> using these
          substitutions:
</p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>x=\sin(\theta)</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>u=1-x^2</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <conclusion>
<p>
          Finish <xref ref="OddSinPower">example</xref> using each of the
          substitutions above. Do you get the same solution as before?
</p>
        </conclusion>
      </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="SinCosOddPower">
<introduction>
      <p>
        Compute the integral
        <m>\int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^3(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m> by:
      </p>
</introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Saving one of the cosines and converting everthing else into sines.  
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Saving one of the sines and converting everthing else into cosines.  
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
