    </exercise>

    <example xml:id="SinCosEven">
      <p>
        What happens if you don’t have an odd power of sine or cosine? For
        example, suppose you have
        <m>\int\sin^2(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Saving a sine or cosine would lead to an integrand with a square root, which we are trying to avoid, if we
        can help it. In this case, there are a couple of trigonometric
        identities that can help. They the Half-Angle formlas:
        <me>
          \sin^2(\theta) = \frac12\left(1-\cos(2\theta)\right) \text{ and }
          \cos^2(\theta)=\frac12\left(1+\cos(2\theta)\right) 
          </me>.
          Using  these identities in our integral we see that
          <md>
            <mrow>\int\sin^2(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}\amp=\frac14\int(1-\cos(2\theta))(1+\cos(2\theta))\dx{\theta}</mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp=\frac14\int (1-\cos^2(2\theta))\dx{\theta}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp=\frac{1}{4}\int\sin^2(2\theta)\dx{\theta}
            </mrow>
          </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Using the Half-Angle formula again we obtain 
        <me>
          \frac{1}{4}\int\sin^2(2\theta)\dx{\theta} =
          \frac18\int(1-\cos(4\theta))\dx{\theta} =
          \frac18\left(\theta-\frac14\sin(4\theta)\right)+c
        </me> 
      </p>
    </example>
      <problem>
        <p>
          Show that we  get the same result if we use the Double
          Angle formula: <m>\sin(2\theta)=2\sin(\theta)\cos(\theta)</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>
    <example>
<p>
      <m>
        \int\sec^4(\theta)\tan^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}
      </m>
</p> 
      <p>
        In this example, we can save a <m>\sec^2(\theta)</m> as part of the
        differential and use the identity <m>\sec^2(\theta)=1+\tan^2(\theta)</m>
        to change everything else into an expression in tangent. Since the secant is to an even power this again
        avoids square roots, which is the general idea.
        <md>
          <mrow>\int \sec^4(\theta)\tan^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}\amp=\int
          \sec^2(\theta)\tan^2(\theta)\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</mrow>
          <mrow>
            \int(1+\tan^2(\theta))\tan^2(\theta)\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}
          </mrow>
        </md>
        Letting <m>y=\tan(\theta)</m>  we have
        <m>\dx{y}=\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>, so we obtain

        <md>
          <mrow>\int(1+y^2)y^2\dx{y}=\int(y^2+y^4)\dx{y}=\frac{y^3}{3}+\frac{y^5}{5}+c=\frac{\tan^3(\theta)}{3}+\frac{\tan^5(\theta)}{5}+c</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>

    <example>
      <p>
        If tangent occurs to an odd power, we can save a tangent and a secant
        as part of the differential and use the same identity to convert
        everything else to secant.
        <me>
          \int\sec^2(\theta)\tan^3(\theta)\dx{\theta} =
          \int\sec^2(\theta)\tan^2(\theta)\sec(\theta)\tan(\theta)\dx{\theta{}}=\int\sec^2(\theta)(\sec^2(\theta)-1)\sec(\theta)\tan(\theta)\dx{\theta}
          </me>.
          Letting <m>u=\sec(\theta)</m> we have
          <me>
            \int u^2(u^2-1)\dx{u}=\int
            (u^4-u^2)\dx{u}=\frac{u^5}{5}-\frac{u^3}{3}+c=\frac{\sec^5(\theta)}{5}-\frac{\sec^3(\theta)}{3}+c
            </me>.
      </p>
    </example>

