  <section>
    <title>Back to Logistic Growth: Partial Fractions</title>
<subsection>

<title>Intro</title>

    <p>
      Recall that in Section 6.4 of <q>
Differential Calculus
</q>
 we had this example for
        logistic growth
        <men xml:id="LogisticGrowthFromDiffCalc">
          \dfdx{y}{t}=.01y\left(1-\frac{y}{100}\right)=0.0001y(100-y)
          </men>.
          In that chapter, we analyzed this growth rate to draw a qualitative
          graph of <m>y=y(t)</m>, but we could
          not produce specific values of <m>t</m> for where things happened,
          because we didn’t have a formula for <m>y(t)</m>. We  now have the
          techniques needed to find <m>y(t)</m>.
    </p>
<aside>
      <title>Note to Self</title>
      <p>
        Turn this into a PreTeXt reference.  
</p>
</aside>
    <p>
      First we separate the
      variables:<me>\frac{\dx{y}}{y(100-y)}=0.0001y\dx{t} </me>.  To integrate
      the left-hand side, we could expand the denominator to complete the
      square and apply the appropriate trigonometric substitution.
    </p>
    <p>
      As we’ve mentioned before, all mathematical models are simplifications
      of reality, and typically are modified to take into account more
      complexities. For example, consider the following modification of the logistic
      model above
      <me>\dfdx{y}{t}=0.01y\left(1-\frac{y}{100}\right)\left(\frac{y}{10}\right)=0.0001y(100-y)(y-1)</me>.
      In this case, <m>10</m> is called the <em>minimum viability level of the population.</em> (Why?) Solving this would require that we compute the integral
      <me>\int \frac{\dx{y}}{y(100-y)(y-10)}</me>.
      This form of this integral does not suggest any obvious trigonometric substitution so we will need a new idea.
    </p>

    <p>
      The next technique is wholly algebraic in nature. The trick to try and
      separate the integrand into <term>partial fractions</term> each of
      which will be easier to integrate than the original. For example,
      consider the expression <m>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}</m>. With begin by
      making a reasonable, educated guess
      that such a fraction can be written as
      <m>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}=\frac{A}{y}+\frac{B}{100-y}</m>, where <m>A</m>
      and <m>B</m> are constant to be determined. We can see if this guess
      pans out by combining the partial fractions to obtain the original.
      <me>\frac{A}{y}+\frac{B}{100-y}=\frac{A(100-y)+By}{y(100-y)}=\frac{10A+(B-A)y}{y(100-y)}</me>
      Comparing this with <m>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}=</m> we see that if they are
      to be equal we must have <m>100A=1</m> and <m>B-A=0</m>. Therefore
      <m>A=B=\frac{1}{100}</m>. Thus
      <me>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}=\frac{1/100}{y}+\frac{1/100}{100-y}</me>. Substituting
      into the original integral we see that
      <md>
        <mrow>
        \int\frac{\dx{y}}{y(100-y)}\amp=\int\frac{1/100}{y}\dx{y}+\int\frac{1/100}{100-y}\dx{y}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{100}\left(\int\frac{\dx{y}}{y}+\int\frac{\dx{y}}{100-y}\right)</mrow>
      </md>
      and so
      <mdn>
        <mrow xml:id="PartFrac1">\int\frac{\dx{y}}{y(100-y)}=\frac{1}{100}\left(\ln(y)-\ln(100-y)\right)+C</mrow>
      </mdn>
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Comment</title>
      <p>
        This isn't really a guess. There is a theorem from algebra that says
        that there will always be constants <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> such that
        <m>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}=\frac{A}{y}+\frac{B}{100-y}</m> but since we
        haven't discussed this yet we'll just roll with it for now.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <exercise>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use <xref ref="PartFrac1">equation</xref> to find <m>y</m> for the
            logistic growth model with the initial
            condition <m>y(0)=0</m>
            <me>\dfdx{y}{t}=0.01y\left(1-\frac{y}{100}\right)\hskip5mm y(0)=0</me>
            for the case when <m>0\lt100</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve the same problem for the case where <m>y\gt 100</m>.
          </p>
          <aside>
            <title>Comment</title>
            <p>
              This is a spot
              where you need to look at the absolute value in the logarithm. We told
              you it comes up occasionally.
            </p>
          </aside>
        </statement>
      </task>

    </exercise>
</subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="PartialFractionSubsection">
      <title>The Partial Fraction Decomposition</title>
      <p>
        Now that we've seen that decomposing a ratio of
        polynomials (these are called  <term>rational functions</term>) into a sum of partial
        fractions is possible, we'll look for  a systematic way of doing this for any <term>
        rational function
        </term>. Our method will  hinge on the following theoretical, algebraic fact.
      </p>
      <p>
        Suppose we have two polynomials <m>p(x)</m> and <m>q(x)</m> which have
        no common factors (other than constants). Then there are polynomials
        <m>r(x)</m> and <m>s(x)</m> such that
        <me>r(x)\cdot{}p(x)+s(x)\cdot{}q(x)=1</me>.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ElementaryPartFracDecomp">
        <p>
          For example notice that if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are constants then
          <m>x+a</m> and <m>x-b</m> have no common factors. Since
          <m>(x+a)-(x+b)=a-b</m> it follows  that

          <me>\frac{1}{a-b}(x+a)+\frac{-1}{a-b}(x+b)=1</me>.

        </p>
<aside>
          <title>Comment</title>
          <p>
            Notice that since  <m>\frac{1}{a-b}</m> and <m>\frac{-1}{a-b}</m> are constants they are polynomials of degree zero.
          </p>
</aside>
      </example>
      <p>
        Our approach to the problem in <xref ref="ElementaryPartFracDecomp">example</xref>was  somewhat ad-hoc. We will evantualy need a more systematic approach but it will be useful to look at some more examples first. So for now we will use an
        (educated) guess and check method. Notice that in the <xref ref="ElementaryPartFracDecomp">example</xref> we had
        <me>\frac{1}{(x+a)(x+b)}=\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}(x+a)+\frac{-1}{a-b}(x+b)}{(x+a)(x+b)}=
        \frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{x+b}+\frac{\frac{-1}{a-b}}{x+a}=\frac{\frac{-1}{x+a}}{x+a}\frac{\frac{1}{x-b}}{x+b}</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        It is generally true that if <m>r(x)\cdot p(x+s(x)\cdot q(x)=1</m>
        then
        <me>\frac{1}{p(x)\cdot{}q(x)}=\frac{r(x)\cdot{}p(x)+s(x)\cdot{}q(x)}{p(x)\cdot{}q(x)}=
        \frac{s(x)}{p(x)}+\frac{r(x)}{q(x)}</me>. Multiplying by <m>t(x)</m>
        we have <me>\frac{t(x)}{p(x)\cdot{}q(x)}= \frac{t(x)\cdot
        s(x)}{p(x)}+\frac{t(x)\cdot{}r(x)}{q(x)}</me>.  Setting
        <m>A(x)=t(x)\cdot{}s(x)</m> and <m>B(x)=t(x)\cdot r(x)</m> gives
        <md>
          <mrow>\frac{t(x)}{p(x)\cdot{}q(x)}=
          \frac{A(x)}{p(x)}+\frac{B(x)}{q(x)}</mrow>
          </md>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Everything we've just shown assumes that if <m>p(x)</m> and
        <m>q(x)</m> are known then <m>r(x)</m> and <m>s(x)</m> can be found so
        that <m>r(x)\cdot p(x)+ s(x)\cdot q(x)=1</m>. For arbitrary functions
        this is a very restrictive condition. However as we observed above, if
        <m>p(x)</m> and <m>q(x)</m> are polynomial then the existence of
        <m>r(x)</m> and <m>s(x)</m> is guaranteed. Thus for polynomials the
        <term> Partial Fraction Decomposition </term> is also guaranteed.
      </p>

      <p>
        We formalize this in the following theorem.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="PartialFractionDecomp">

        <title>The Partial Fraction Decomposition (PFD)</title>
        <p>
          If <m>P(x)</m>, <m>Q(x)</m>, and <m>R(x)</m> are polynomials with
          <m>\deg(P)\lt\deg(Q)+ \deg(R)</m>  the there exist  polynomials
          <m>A(x)</m> and <m>B(x)</m>,
          <m>\deg{A}\lt\deg{Q}</m> and <m>\deg(B)\lt\deg(R)</m>, such that
          <me>\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)\cdot{}R(x)} = \frac{A(x)}{Q(x)}+\frac{B(x)}{R(x)}</me>.
        </p>
      </theorem>

      <p>
        As stated in <xref ref="PartialFractionDecomp">Theorem</xref> the PFD is very comprehensive. We will
      </p>

    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section> <title>Areas and Integration</title> <p> Recall, much
  earlier, that we examined the catenary (hanging chain).  We showed
  that the catenary was not a parabola as Galileo had mentioned.  The
  idea of a catenary was (and is) important in engineering in the
  construction of arches.  Masons before Galileo’s time were aware of
  the fact that the “best” arches were in the shape of an inverted
  catenary, and they constructed wooden frames for their stone utilizing
  a hanging chain for the correct shape.  This can be seen in the
  following example.  </p> <example> <title>Stone Arch Bridge</title>
  <p> 
Consider one half of a stone arch bridge as drawn below. 
  </p> 
 <figure>
<caption>
Schematic of a stone arch
</caption>
  <image source="StoneArch.png" width="40%">
